WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:10.840
Ladies and gentlemen, friends of Tennessee, from time to time on this program, other visitors

00:10.840 --> 00:17.600
and I have had an occasion to say something about the Tom Bigby Waterway in which I have

00:17.600 --> 00:20.880
been interested for a long, long time.

00:20.880 --> 00:25.960
I think it's important that all Tennesseans and people in Mississippi, Alabama, Kentucky

00:25.960 --> 00:30.280
and the whole nation know about this very remarkable project.

00:30.280 --> 00:36.240
For our section of the country, I think it is the most important proposed development

00:36.240 --> 00:42.280
that we have had since the coming of the Tennessee Valley Authority back in 1933.

00:42.280 --> 00:48.880
It's going to affect our communities and our industry, our agriculture and there will

00:48.880 --> 00:55.680
be a great advancement for every section of our state and several adjacent states.

00:55.680 --> 01:01.800
To describe and talk about the Tennessee Tom Bigby Waterway and more detail, I have

01:01.800 --> 01:08.160
invited and I appreciate his acceptance Colonel Robert C. Marshall, who is the Assistant

01:08.160 --> 01:13.560
Director of the Civil Works Division of the Corps of Engineers under whose jurisdiction

01:13.560 --> 01:15.680
this waterway comes.

01:15.680 --> 01:20.800
To come and tell us something about it and to tell the meaning of it and what's going

01:20.800 --> 01:24.520
to be done to the listeners over this station.

01:24.520 --> 01:28.640
Colonel Marshall is awfully good to have you with us and we appreciate very much your coming

01:28.640 --> 01:29.640
here.

01:29.640 --> 01:35.160
You've been in the Corps of Engineers for many years, I believe, have you not?

01:35.160 --> 01:36.840
Well, about 20, sir.

01:36.840 --> 01:41.880
And you were telling me that during the war you spent some time in the volunteer state.

01:41.880 --> 01:42.880
I did indeed.

01:42.880 --> 01:50.200
It was my pleasure to be assigned to Camp Forest, Tennessee, Nertelahoma, and also to engage

01:50.200 --> 01:52.680
in what were then known as a Tennessee maneuver.

01:52.680 --> 01:57.800
Well, Camp Forest was a very important military establishment.

01:57.800 --> 02:04.160
It has gone as you may know and Arnold Engineering Development Center occupies much of the same

02:04.160 --> 02:09.000
territory that we would welcome you back to Tennessee whenever you can come.

02:09.000 --> 02:10.000
I thank you, sir.

02:10.000 --> 02:14.800
Now, Colonel Marshall, tell us something about the Tom Bigby Waterway.

02:14.800 --> 02:23.120
It shows where it starts and where it goes to and a little bit about the history of it

02:23.120 --> 02:24.120
if you would.

02:24.120 --> 02:31.720
Well, sir, the Tennessee Tom Bigby, as it is known now, is designed to connect the Tom Bigby

02:31.720 --> 02:35.200
River with the Tennessee River.

02:35.200 --> 02:39.280
This route has been considered for many years.

02:39.280 --> 02:44.600
The early French settlers looked at the divide just below the Tennessee and hoped to build

02:44.600 --> 02:50.040
the canal to the south in order to connect to Tennessee River with the Gulf.

02:50.040 --> 02:53.840
Now, the Tom Bigby River comes up to about where this arrow is.

02:53.840 --> 02:54.840
Is that correct?

02:54.840 --> 02:55.840
Yes, sir.

02:55.840 --> 03:01.480
The natural stream terminates about this area and then we would go into a canal type operation.

03:01.480 --> 03:07.560
As I recall, back in the 1870s, the Corps of Engineers actually recommended the building of

03:07.560 --> 03:12.760
a shallow channel connecting the Gulf with the Tennessee River.

03:12.760 --> 03:13.760
Is that?

03:13.760 --> 03:20.640
In 1875, the Corps of Engineers rendered a report to the Congress indicating that a four-foot

03:20.640 --> 03:29.080
channel could be constructed, essentially along this alignment, at the cost of only $1,700,000.

03:29.080 --> 03:30.080
Yes.

03:30.080 --> 03:31.080
Another...

03:31.080 --> 03:38.800
Picklick Bamm was built here, I believe, about 1935 or six.

03:38.800 --> 03:47.840
And that is toward Chattanooga, where the canal, where the waterway would enter.

03:47.840 --> 03:53.760
And how water that does make it possible for water to come down to the ten locks of the

03:53.760 --> 03:57.040
Tennessee Tom Bigby waterway.

03:57.040 --> 03:58.040
Is that...

03:58.040 --> 03:59.040
Yes, sir.

03:59.040 --> 04:03.920
Just like Gattu and Malayka on the top of Panama Canal makes it possible.

04:04.640 --> 04:09.600
Yes, sir, the fact that Tickwick Pool is available and has an adequate supply of water,

04:09.600 --> 04:16.200
which could be diverted to the canal, will permit the operation of these various locks.

04:16.200 --> 04:18.920
And in fact makes it canal much more feasible.

04:18.920 --> 04:25.760
I was in the House of Representatives at the time back in 1946 when the Tennessee Tom Bigby

04:25.760 --> 04:29.720
was approved by the Congress in that year.

04:29.720 --> 04:36.920
And then I believe that there was some restudy, a proclamation for a restudy in 1956,

04:36.920 --> 04:41.640
or the engineers didn't make a restudy about that time.

04:41.640 --> 04:42.640
That's correct, sir.

04:42.640 --> 04:48.640
There was some debate and perhaps some doubts regarding the economic aspect of the project.

04:48.640 --> 04:55.640
And so we were directed to undertake a restudy of the economics, which we have recently finished

04:55.640 --> 04:57.880
and have under the report.

04:57.880 --> 05:01.560
And what is the report, the economics of this great development?

05:01.560 --> 05:07.400
Well, fundamentally, as in all our projects, the determination was made of the total cost

05:07.400 --> 05:08.400
of the project.

05:08.400 --> 05:13.640
It's about $250 million, a little more than that.

05:13.640 --> 05:20.120
And then based on the 50-year, expected, at least 50-year, expected economic life of the

05:20.120 --> 05:23.640
project, an annual cost was determined.

05:23.640 --> 05:30.360
An annual cost of about $12 million, and compared to that annual cost, an annual benefit

05:30.360 --> 05:32.440
was also determined.

05:32.440 --> 05:37.560
And we then found that the benefit exceeded the cost, and therefore that it was, in fact,

05:37.560 --> 05:41.200
an economically justifiable project.

05:41.200 --> 05:46.680
And how much traffic on the waterway to you in this debate will be the average over

05:46.680 --> 05:48.640
a period of 50 years?

05:48.640 --> 05:52.880
About 12 million, a little over 12 million tons per year, sir.

05:52.880 --> 05:58.640
Now the details as I understand it, how deep will the waterway be?

05:58.640 --> 06:03.760
It will be a nine-foot project initially throughout its length.

06:03.760 --> 06:10.200
In constructing the ten locks, which you mentioned earlier, we will provide for 13-foot

06:10.200 --> 06:17.480
depths, should in the later life of the project traffic warrant a construction to that added

06:17.480 --> 06:18.480
depth.

06:18.480 --> 06:25.360
But fundamentally it will provide for a nine-foot navigable waterway, a varying widths 150 feet

06:25.360 --> 06:28.800
in some sections and wider in others.

06:28.800 --> 06:36.920
Yes, but eventually if it needed to be done, it could be a 13-foot depth, and the locks

06:36.920 --> 06:42.600
will be built so as to accommodate traffic with 13-foot, that's correct.

06:42.600 --> 06:43.600
That's correct.

06:43.600 --> 06:52.460
Then we will have a slack waterway from the Oehaw River here at New York, the Duke of

06:52.460 --> 06:53.460
course.

06:53.460 --> 06:54.460
This is a Tennessee lake.

06:54.460 --> 06:59.800
Sometimes it's called a Kentucky lake, but really the part in Tennessee is a slack water

06:59.800 --> 07:00.800
lake.

07:00.800 --> 07:07.200
And then the slack water all the way down to the Gulf so that the barges and ships can go

07:07.200 --> 07:11.320
either way to the Oehaw in slack waters.

07:11.320 --> 07:13.320
That's fundamentally correct.

07:13.320 --> 07:18.940
If they want to go up the Tennessee to Knoxville, the water, of course the river is navigable

07:18.940 --> 07:21.840
and the water is comparatively slack.

07:21.840 --> 07:30.840
Then of course there is a canal between the Kentucky lake and the Cumberland bark lake on

07:30.840 --> 07:35.920
the Cumberland River, which will make it available for traffic on the Cumberland.

07:35.920 --> 07:44.500
What will be shipped down the canal largely and figuring the economic benefits of Colonel

07:44.500 --> 07:45.840
Marshall?

07:45.840 --> 07:53.800
We have predicted based on comparison of rates and market areas, areas, growth of population,

07:53.800 --> 08:00.480
and the other factors, we predict a considerable movement of middle-western grains either to

08:00.480 --> 08:07.040
the Gulf and to southerly markets or perhaps to the Alabama Mississippi Georgia area.

08:07.040 --> 08:09.320
This would be feed grains, primarily.

08:09.320 --> 08:12.000
Our feed grains are farmers and tonuses.

08:12.000 --> 08:13.000
Yes, they are.

08:13.000 --> 08:14.000
Absolutely.

08:14.000 --> 08:20.640
We also visualize that there is a potential movement of coal from Tennessee to markets in

08:20.640 --> 08:22.200
the south.

08:22.200 --> 08:28.840
Primarily the markets would be in the steam generation of electricity.

08:28.840 --> 08:34.280
Perhaps in Florida or even places where they use gas at the present time.

08:34.280 --> 08:35.280
Yes, sir.

08:35.280 --> 08:44.680
Florida right now is a large consumer of Tennessee and Kentucky coal for its generation of electricity

08:44.680 --> 08:50.320
and we visualize that coal will remain competitive in that area.

08:50.320 --> 08:55.720
As we all know there is a great deal of coal in the Cumberland section of Kentucky and Tennessee,

08:55.720 --> 09:04.000
which we hope will be subject to being barged on the Cumberland River.

09:04.000 --> 09:10.040
This east and middle Tennessee section has a great deal of coal so there is northern Alabama

09:10.040 --> 09:16.240
and of course western Kentucky is rich in coal so you do envision a great deal of coal

09:16.240 --> 09:18.240
traffic down to the Gulf.

09:18.240 --> 09:20.960
It's a great potential, yes sir.

09:20.960 --> 09:25.880
Then how about from the Gulf back north among the waterway?

09:25.880 --> 09:32.200
Primarily a waterway of this nature inherently lends itself to the movement of bulk commodities

09:32.200 --> 09:36.600
and probably the most significant is petroleum products.

09:36.600 --> 09:43.640
Well, what of course benefit consumers along the waterway by virtue of less expensive

09:43.640 --> 09:49.560
transportation of heating fuels and gasoline.

09:49.560 --> 09:58.640
And there is also a potential and a predictable movement of fertilizers from the Caribbean

09:58.640 --> 10:01.000
and Florida area to the north.

10:01.000 --> 10:04.560
A phosphate and things that that's ordered.

10:04.560 --> 10:09.480
So it is going to be one of the great important waterways in our country.

10:09.480 --> 10:14.000
The colonel as you know, they could people along the Mississippi and Memphis, Dixburg

10:14.000 --> 10:22.600
and New Orleans have now joined in recommending the development of the Tom Bay because they

10:22.600 --> 10:27.320
do not feel that it meant the in that it's going to interfere with the good traffic that

10:27.320 --> 10:29.680
they have on the Mississippi River.

10:29.680 --> 10:31.160
I think so, sir.

10:31.160 --> 10:36.200
I think Mississippi, the state of Mississippi, Alabama, Tennessee and more recently Kentucky

10:36.200 --> 10:42.320
have joined together and formed an authority and this authority and hence Mississippi and

10:42.320 --> 10:48.960
the other states recognize the advantage, the flexibility and the cheap transportation

10:48.960 --> 10:50.760
that is afforded by this waterway.

10:50.760 --> 10:57.440
Yes, there is a comeback between the states of Mississippi, Alabama, Tennessee and Kentucky

10:57.440 --> 11:03.400
and perhaps some other which was approved by Congress and they do have an association

11:03.400 --> 11:07.560
that's been very effective in pushing the Tom Bay Bay waterway.

11:07.560 --> 11:12.880
A colonel, I know this isn't in the budget because your report didn't come to the Congress

11:12.880 --> 11:18.800
in time for it to be or rather to the administration in time for it to be put in the budget but it's

11:18.800 --> 11:26.960
my understanding that you can efficiently expand or your capability of expanding for the

11:26.960 --> 11:32.840
next year, next fiscal year is a million dollars in advanced planning for this waterway.

11:32.840 --> 11:40.280
It would be actually our planning is pretty well along so it would not only permit the completion

11:40.280 --> 11:48.200
of some added detail plans but actual construction could be initiated at the, we would start at

11:48.200 --> 11:54.360
the most southerly lock, the Gainesville lock which is this area.

11:54.360 --> 12:00.400
And so that if we get the million dollars as we hope to and on the appropriations committee

12:00.400 --> 12:05.760
we are working for it for this next fiscal year you can actually begin some construction.

12:05.760 --> 12:06.760
That's correct.

12:06.760 --> 12:13.240
I understand that this may be a place where atomic energy will be used to a good advantage

12:13.240 --> 12:20.200
on the blasting and the moving of dirt it may be necessary as part of the contemplation.

12:20.200 --> 12:27.640
This project does lend itself to the peaceful application of nuclear energy particularly

12:27.640 --> 12:35.240
in the section known as the divide cut which is just south of the Tennessee River.

12:35.240 --> 12:44.560
In this area the depth of cut is approximately 150 feet and by use of nuclear explosives

12:44.560 --> 12:54.400
detonated below the surface with no fallout or other radiation problems this excavation

12:54.400 --> 13:03.800
could be constructed at a cost at least 10% less expensive than if conventional excavation

13:03.800 --> 13:06.120
methods were used.

13:06.120 --> 13:15.120
So we do hope that the current test series and perhaps subsequent test series will provide

13:15.120 --> 13:22.440
the engineering and safety information necessary for us to more accurately determine these

13:22.440 --> 13:31.120
costs based on current information we are confident that it is feasible to employ nuclear

13:31.120 --> 13:33.120
explosives in this area.

13:33.120 --> 13:38.320
Well ladies and gentlemen I know that you've enjoyed having this explanation of this great

13:38.320 --> 13:44.720
new imaginative and wonderful project that's going to come our way by the explanation that's

13:44.720 --> 13:49.560
been made by Colonel Marshall and we thank you very much for being with us today my

13:49.560 --> 13:50.560
pleasure.

13:50.560 --> 13:51.560
Thank you.

13:51.560 --> 13:58.920
Until next to the program that's all for now.

